  "prompt": "Biochemistry: What are the most common types of protein damage caused by reactive nitrogen species?",
  "response": "Reactive nitrogen species (RNS) can cause several types of damage to proteins, affecting their structure and function. The most common types of protein damage caused by RNS include:\n\n1. **Nitration of Tyrosine Residues**: One of the most well-known modifications caused by RNS, particularly peroxynitrite (ONOO\u207b), is the nitration of tyrosine residues to form 3-nitrotyrosine. This modification can alter protein function by affecting binding sites or enzyme activity.\n\n2. **Formation of Protein Carbonyls**: RNS can lead to the oxidative modification of amino acids, resulting in the formation of carbonyl groups (such as aldehydes and ketones) on proteins. This can occur due to the oxidation of side chains of lysine, arginine, or proline residues and can lead to misfolding and aggregation.\n\n3. **Disulfide Bond Formation**: RNS can promote the formation of disulfide bonds between cysteine residues, potentially resulting in improper folding or cross-linking of proteins, which can affect their stability and function.\n\n4. **Modification of Protein Amino Acids**: Besides tyrosine, other amino acids such as tryptophan and histidine can also undergo modifications by RNS, impacting their function and the overall structure of the protein.\n\n5. **Alteration of Protein Conformation**: The modifications caused by RNS can lead to changes in the protein\u2019s tertiary and quaternary structures, affecting its stability and activity.\n\n6. **Fragmentation and Aggregation**: Severe oxidative damage can lead to protein fragmentation and aggregation, which is often associated with various diseases, including neurodegenerative disorders.\n\nThese modifications can disrupt normal cellular processes, lead to loss of protein activity, promote cellular stress responses, and contribute to various pathological conditions, including inflammation, neurodegenerative diseases, and cancer.",
